{"key":"post-12993086","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12993086</id>\n<content>Those holes are larger than 1/4&quot;.&amp;nbsp; It's going to be hard to fix what's already broken, so leave your cakes in there while you get a new tub and build it right.&amp;nbsp; Use 1/4&quot; holes every two inches over all six sides.&amp;nbsp; Place four to five inches of well drained perlite in and you'll be set.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Bear in mind, a 1/2&quot; hole has four times the area of a 1/4&quot; hole, and will screw up the airflow.&amp;nbsp; You want air exchange while holding humidity.&amp;nbsp; I experimented with nearly every drill bit I had before settling on 1/4&quot; holes.&amp;nbsp; Cheap analog hygrometers from pet stores are as crappy as 'most' digital ones.&amp;nbsp; The problem is once the electronic sensors get damp, they quit working right.&amp;nbsp; If you can find a quality analog hygrometer with a human hair mechanism, it will be perfect.&amp;nbsp; The chinese crap they sell now isn't worth wasting money on.&amp;nbsp; Build the terrarium per the tek and it will work.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;I don't even have a hygrometer in my underground mushroom farm.&amp;nbsp; I've learned to 'read' the mushrooms themselves and the gravel on the floor to know when it's right.&amp;nbsp; Once a person gains experience, the hygrometers can be taken out.&amp;nbsp; While you're learning the ropes, you need a hygrometer that actually works though.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12993099</next>\n<prev>12993028</prev>\n<first>12992687</first>\n<last>12997891</last>\n<when>1280804776</when>\n<utime>08/03/10 06:06 AM</utime>\n</post>"}